subSubSection.paragraph:
Gall
(
Figs 1–4
). Asexual generation. Gall is 
1–3 mm
in diameter, subsphaerical to ellipsoid in shape, with the longest axis parallel to the leaf surface. Young growing galls are red, with warty surface covered with translucent tiny blister-like humps (
Figs 2–3
); when mature they turn reddish-brown. Galls are fixed to the median or lateral veins of lower leaf surface through a short, whitish stalk; typically 3–8 or even more galls can be found on one leaf (maximum number observed is 17 galls on a leaf). The gall wall is thin (
Fig. 4
), spongy on its inner surface and slightly woody externally. A single larval chamber is present in each gall.
